V. 36, 37. Some Mss. have aptius for inscius and this reading is adopted by many edd. as a foundation for other improvements. They say, with some justice, that timuitque mortem is a feeble climax to the ponderous lines which precede: that Hor. is not likely to have used hic of the same man who has just been called ille (1. 32) and that mortem and vitam are meant to be contrasted and should therefore occur in the same sentence. Hence Bentley and many others read timuitque mortem Hinc unde vitam sumeret aptius: i.e. ‘ feared death
